Retrieving a saved Wi-Fi password in Arch Linux using NetworkManager is straightforward, as it stores connection profiles in plain text (assuming you have root privileges).

Here are the two best ways to do it.

Method 1: The Terminal (Recommended)
NetworkManager stores individual connection files in /etc/NetworkManager/system-connections/.

List your saved connections to find the exact name of your Wi-Fi:

Bash
nmcli connection show
Read the configuration file for that specific network (replace SSID_NAME with your actual network name):

Bash
sudo cat /etc/NetworkManager/system-connections/SSID_NAME.nmconnection
Find the password: Look for the [wifi-security] section. The password is listed next to psk=.

Method 2: The nmcli Command
If you prefer a cleaner output without digging through the whole file, you can use the command-line tool directly.

Run this command:

Bash
nmcli -s show SSID_NAME | grep psk
Note: The -s (or --show-secrets) flag is crucial here. Without it, NetworkManager will hide the password field for security reasons.

Method 3: The GUI Way (If you have a Desktop Environment)
If you’re running GNOME, KDE Plasma, or XFCE:

Open your Network Settings.

Select the Wi-Fi tab and click the Settings/Gear icon next to your current network.

Navigate to the Wi-Fi Security tab.

Check the Show password box.

Why can't I see it?
If the psk line is empty or missing, your password might be stored in a keyring (like GNOME Keyring or KDE Wallet) rather than the configuration file. In that case, you'll need to open your specific desktop "Passwords and Keys" application to find it.

